result.execSummary:
The defendant Antoine Delve Young was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Antoine Delve Young is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Antoine Delve Young was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
As to Count 1: Court ordered defendant to serve 45 days in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence, with goodtime credit.  Huber privileges for work.
Court ordered defendant to pay all mandatory costs, penalties, and surcharges by 08/22/2016 or an immediate entry of a civil judgment is ordered by the court.  
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief and Sentencing Referral Form received and filed.

Defendant Antoine Delve Young in court with attorney Colin P. McGinn.  Brittany Skye Kachingwe appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
As to Count 1:  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.
As to Count 2:  Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered Count 2 dismissed.
